n75% 19 United Cor Del... K 0 36% 36% 36%\n158% 99 United Fruit 73 107% 107% 107J4-\nSl!* 13% Unit E C0a1.... 2 12% 12% 12%+\nJURY CONVENES\nfITALEXANDRIA\nALEXANDRIA. Va.. Dec.- 9.\u2014\nThe regular 7 semi-annual grand\njury convened this morning. Rob\nert T. Colvin was appointed fore\nman. Twenty-three informations\nwill be filed by Commonwealth\u2019s\nAttorney Albert V. Bryan, among\nthem the cases of Richard Acton,\ncharged with the fatal shooting\nof 17-year-old Irving Guchert after\nan argument in the greenhouses\nformerly owned by Guchert\u2019s\nfather and in which Acton was\nemployed as watchman.\nThe cases of Albert Poss. Henry\nPoss and Charles Poss, charged\nwith assisting Dr. W. C. West,\nand e.her charges will also be\npresented. The remainder of the\ndocket is composed of housebreak\ning and felonious assault cases.\nThe city's loitering ordinance\nreceived another blow this morn\ning when a colored girl charged\nwith loitering on the street was\ndismissed. Although there have\nbeen nearly a dozen persons\ncharged with loafing, only one\nperson has been convicted under\nthe ordinance.\nAll the other cases before police\ncourt were connected with liquor\nlaw violations. Two colored men\nwere found guilty and one. Claude\nButler, up for the third time, was\ngiven a six-months jail sentence.\nA colored man and woman\nwere shot last night in the house,\n527 North Patrick St., of Jack\nHolmes, colored, of North Caro\nlina.\nAccording to the story told by\nEugene Price, one of the victims,\nHolmes came looking for trouble,\nand Price took a gun away from\nhim and Holmes a few minutes\nlater went out and came back\nwith another gun with which he\nopened fire as he entered the\ndoor.\nOne of three shots struck Price\nin the side, slightly injuring him\nand another struck Phoebe Rey\nnolds. colored, in the back caus\ning a serious wound. Holmes es\ncaped. The Reynolds woman was\ntaken to the hospital and treated\nby Dr. Delaney.\nAccording to City Treasurer\nRoger C. Sullivan, the voting list\nfor the council election in June\nwill be less than that of the elec\ntion last November, but W\u2019ill be\nbigger than any previous voting\nlist for the council, from 9 a. m.\nto 9 p. m, Wednesday and Thurs\nday the office was besieged by\ntaxpayers.\nFOREIGN BONDS\nFrench 4 s 39\u20194\nFrench 5s 4 2 r\nFrench premium 5s 514\nFrench Internal Ks 41%\nBritish Victory 4s 426\nBritish War Loan 5s 486\nItalian Cons 5s 43\nBelgian Restoration 5s 26\nBelgian Premium 5s 28%\nBANK STATEMENT\nWashington Clearing House,\n$4,424,371.41.\nNew York Clearing House ex\nchange, $661,000,000.\nNew York Clearing House Bal\nance. $151,000,000.\nTreasury Balance, $94,582,-\n437.18.\nCustoms Receipts. $8,964,745,19.\nMONDAT, DECEMBER 9,\n\u2018Heavy Petting\u2019 Ruins\nChances of Happy\nMarriages\nNEW YORK, Dec. 9\u2014Chances\nof happy marriages are ruined\nby \u2022'heavy petting.\u201d\nThat\u2019s what the Rev. A.\nHerbert Gray, visiting London\nclergyman, told 300 Columbia\nUniversity students at a meet\ning of the religious forum. Dr.\nGray said:\n\"Heavy petting lessens the\nchances of happy marriage. You,\nin America, are being hum\nbugged on a collosal scale when\nyou are told that marriage is a\nfailure and something that\ndoesn\u2019t last. It\u2019s not the insti\ntution that\u2019s being ruined; it is\nthe men and women.\u201d\nThe single standard, he said,\nis all right, but the tragedy is\nthat women have gone down to\nthe men\u2019s low standard instead\nof waiting for the men to come\nup to their own.\nMINS BEER\nNEW YORK, Dec. 9\u2014While the\nUnited States Government waited\nthree years to establish its right\nin Federal court to attach the\nequipment of the David Mayer\nBrewing Company, 130,000 gal\nlons of 4\u2019-2 per cent beer, also the\nsubject of attachment proceed\nings, lay in the vats of the com\npany\u2019s plant.\nAfter a series of actions .nd\ncounteractions filed during this\ntime, Federal Judge Frank J.\nColeman decided that the beer\nand equipment, seized on a war\nrant in August, 1926, must be\nreturned to the brewery, owned\nin part by Joseph Herbert.\nDespite the judge\u2019s decision,\nCarl Demig, the company\u2019s robust\nbrewmaster, will stand by the\nvats some time this week and\nopen their pet cocks, while the\noncecontested stuff flows, gallon\nby gallon, into New York\u2019s sewers.\nEver since a Government pad\nlock made it impossible for Demig\nto keep up the plant\u2019s large re\nfrigerators the beer has lain in a\nwarm temperature and calendars\nhave been clogged in Federal\ncourts.\n\"Today,\u201d said Sanford H.\nCohen, attorney for the com\npany, \"the beer, once worth $50,-\n000, is sour and utterly useless.\n\u201cWe contested this case on\nprinciple, but the beer, itself,\nwas of no earthly account months\nago.\u201d\nThough the beer had a content\nof alcohol greater than that al\nlowed by law, Cohen\u2019s estimate of\nits former value, is based, he ssid,\non what it would have sold for\nas near beer.\nWar Shrine Plan\nAward Announced\nCHICAGO. Dec. 9 <I.N.S.).\u2014\nTwo New York architects. Eric\nGugler and Roger Bailey, won a\n$20,000 award by submitting the\nwinning design to-' the Chicago\nwar memorial, it was announced\nhere yesterday.\n1529 Nam* Add 00 High Low 13:11 Ch'g*\nRan** Net\n59% 22 United Ga\u00ab. e 35 334 32% 334+\n55% 12 US C 1 Pine 13 215* 204 2154+ 1%\n23 9 U 8 Diatrib 5 16% 1\u00ab% 16*4+ 4\n72 174 U 8 For Bee 17 28 26 28 +24\n134% 8754 U 8 Freight 54 1054 104% 10554+ 154\n494 18% U 8 Hoffman 4 194 194 194+ 4\n2434 95 Us Alcohol 18 155 153 155 +l4\n354 5 U 8 Leather 2 104 104 14+14\nt 614 15 U 8 Leather ,A.. 5 18 17 18 4\n65 11 U 8 Rubber 3 284 284 204+ 14\n924 404 U 8 Rub let 16 104 504 504+ 14\n724 294 \u00dcBBm Ref... 5 394 384 394+ 4\n\u25a0SB 48 U S Smelt nfd.... 2 514 51 51\n2614 150 U 8 Steel 460 184 182 184 +l4\n1444 137 U 8 Steel Dfd.... 11414 1414 1414\n224 3 Universal Pipe... 14 4 4\n58% 244 Util P 4 Lt 15 354 34% 35