e:\nE. C. Graham, president; Wil\nliam Montgomery, first vice presi\ndent: E. J. Murphy, second vice\npresident; Major Julius I. Peyser,\ntreasurer, and Mrs. Philip S.\nSmith, secretary. Incorporators\ninclude: F. G. Addison, jr., Sibyl\nBaker, Henry M. Brawner,\nCharles F. Carusi, Mrs. Sydney\nA. Cloman, Edward F. Colladav,\nJohn T. Cushing. Charles W.\nDarr. Frederic A. Delano, Victor\nB. Deyber, John Joy Edson,\nJoshua Evans, jr.. W. W. Everett,\nRobert V. Fleming, C. J. Gockeler,\nMrs. Charles A. Goldsmith, C. C.\nGlover, jr., E. C\u201e Graham. Col.\nU. S. Grant, 3d., Mrs. Gilbert\nGrosvenor. Dr. George Havenner,\nFrank J. Hogan, Frank R. Jelleif,\nJohn C. Koons, John Oliver La-\nGorce, Martin A. Leese, Arthur\nD. Marks, L. P. McLachlen, Lowell\nMellett, William Montgomery, E.\nJ. Murphy, Newbold Noyes, John\nJay O\u2019Connor, Hon. Mary O\u2019Toole,\nClaude Owen. Major Julius I.\nPeyser, John Poole, S. J. Prescott,\nHon. Cuno Rudolph, Mrs. Phi\u2019.iu\nS. Smith. W. W. Spaid, Maj. Gm.\nAnton Stephan. Charles H. Tomu\nkins, W. J. Weller, Ben T. Web\nster, George W. White, Dr.\nCharles Stanley White.\nCHICAGO LIVESTOCK\nCHICAGO, Dec. 9.\u2014Hogs\u2014Re\nceipts, 46,000; market i5-25c\nhigher. Top. $9.50; bulk. $8.90\u00a9\n9.40: heavyweight, $9.10\u00a9 9.50;\nmedium weight, $9.20\u00a99.50; light\nweight. $9.00\u00a99.45; light lights,\n$8.60(7/ 9.35; packing sows. s\u00df.oo\u00a9\n8.65; pigs, s\u00df\u00a99; holdovers. 2.000.\nCattle\u2014Receipts, 22,000; mar\nket steady. Calves: Receipts,\n3,500; market 25c lower. Beef\nsteers: Good and choice, $13.00\u00a9\n14.50; common and medium, $9.50\n\u00a913.00; yearlings, slo.oo\u00a9 15.59.\nButcher cattle: Heifers, s\u00df\u00a9 15;\ncows. $6.00\u00a910.50; bulls, $8@11;\ncalves, $13.00\u00a9 15.50: feeder\nsteers, $9.50@11.75; stockersteers,\n$8.50\u00a9 11.00; stocker cows and\nheifers, $6.50\u00a99.50.\nSheep\u2014 28.000: market\n25c lower. Medium and choice\nlambs. $12.50\u00a9 13.25; culls and\ncommon, $9.00\u00a9 11.50: yearlings.\ns9\u00a9 11: common and choice ewes.\nSW6, feeder lambs, sllso\u00a9 12.75.\nSTEEL LEHRS\nADVANCE OP\nSTOCKS\nBy W. 8. COUSINS\nNEW YORK, Dec. 9 (1.N.5.)\nWith the pace of the market\ngradually Increasing, most of the\nIndustrial favorites which led in\nlast week\u2019s \"demonstration\" rose\nbrilliantly in the early trading to\nday. United States Steel carried\nits new spurt to 184, the best price\nrecorded since the November col-\nlapse, to 150, and Anaconda Cop\nper forged ahead to 83 on the a*\nsurance that red metal prices\nwould not be cut. The bulls were\nin the saddle and the bears beat\na hasty retreat in the copper, mo\ntor car, mercantile and specialty\nstocks.\nOver-the-week reports from im-\nportant sections of business and\nindustry were extremely favor.\nable, confirming the accuracy of\nthe stock market\u2019s forecast of\nbusiness revival in last week\u2019s stir\nring upward move. Instead of re\nacting under profit taking, lead.\ning stocks showed their ability to\nadd new gains to those acquired\nlast week.\nThe pre-motor show rise in the\nfavorite motor stocks which\nstarted late last week, was also on v\ntap. Nash was the leadei, with its\nnew 4-point jump to 57%. Chrys-\nler reached a new high on the\nmove at 37%, up while Hupp,\nHudson, Packard and Studebaker\nadvanced about a point on the\naverage. Briggs Manufacturing\nadded a point to last week's 2-\npoint rise and sold at 15%.\nGRAINS OPEN LOWER\nCHICAGO, Dec. 9. <LN.S.).\u2014\nGrains opened lower today,\nWheat was unchanged to %c\no'own; Com down %\u00a9%c and a\nOats %@%c.\nOpening prices:\nWneat\u2014December. $1.24%; 1\nMarch, $132%; July, $1.35% (7/%,\nCorn\u2014December. 89%\u00a9 %c;\nMarch, 95c: May, 97%\u00a9%c; July,\nSB%c.\nOats\u2014December. 46 %c; March,\n48%\u00a949c; May. 50%\u00a9 J 2C.\nHIGHEST BRIDGE OPENED\nCOLORADO SPRINGS. Colo.,\nDecember 9.\u2014The highest sus- x\npension bridge in the world was\nformally dedicated yesterday when j\nthe 1.260-foot span over the Royal\nGorge of the Arkansas River near\nCanon City, Colo., was declared\nopen.\nGl FTSwomenprerer\nNegligees\nTheone sketched is o\nJx 1 pretty offoir of flesh\n~'-V Mi t crepe silk and gearg-\nhlmmed with\necru lace, at\nU Others ot varying\n\nWO\nilr\nif\nPerfume\nby Caron i I\n$35\nsibS f street f\nTIMELY TIPS\nBoard and Room\nGOOD N. E. SECTlON\u2014Attractive\nfront room, with congenial refined\nfamily: excellent* board; 15 minute*\ndowntown.\nHouses for Rent, Unfurnished, I\nD. of C.\nSSS to reliable party; six room*; I\nstucco; h.-w. heat, electricity, cellar,\ngarage; chicken*; one-half acre, etc.\nBusiness Opportunities M\nOLIVE RESTAURANT\u20147th and\nH Sts. N. E.; will sacrifice because\nof business reasons; make your of\nfer at once.\nApartment*, Unfurnished\nMT. RAINIER\u2014Date St. N. E.:\nnew, apartments; a. m. i.: four and\nfive rooms, bath, porch, garage: one x\nblock to Hyattsville bus. N\nRoute* and Estate* for Sale,\nD. of C.\nCAPITOL HILI.\u2014 Facing lour\nstreets; a buy like this is seldom\non the market; 10-room modern\nhome; hardwood floors; arrange\nthree apartments; with a fair cash\npayment. It huits me to sav 1 will I\nhave to sell for 66.950, if sold imme\ndiately.\nSuburban, for Rent\nCHERRYDALE. VA. \u2014Si x-room\nhouse, on Ballston Road; *35 month.\nPereonal*\nVIBRATOR Q-KAY\nLIGHT\u2014For colds, neuritis and soft\nmuscles: treatments. \u00bb2; scalp treat\nment. SI; dally, 9 to 3:30 and Sun\nday, 10 to 5.\nAutomobiles for Sale\nj '*-*\u00a3;**\u2019\u2019\u25a0VROT.ET \u2014Four-rloor se\ndan; $395; easy terms.\nThe above want J and offers\nare only a few of many inter\nesting advertisements you will\nfind in today\u2019s Times and Herald\nclassified advertising section.","height":"30379","width":"23996"}}
